{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VSAHabdkZKhktEBWutf4dy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. `es-cluster-0` and `es-cluster-1` use certificates signed by `es-transport-ca1` (CA1)\n2. `es-cluster-2` uses certificates signed by `es-transport-ca2` (CA2)\n3. The transport CA bundle (`es-transport-ca-bundle` configmap, mounted as `ca.crt`) is what ALL nodes use to verify other nodes' certificates\n4. The `ca.crt` in the bundle currently has BOTH CA1 and CA2 certificates\n\nSo wait, both CAs are already in the bundle. Why is es-cluster-2 having DNS resolution issues?\nActually, looking at the error more carefully—it's a DNS resolution failure for `es-cluster-2.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`, not a TLS issue. The readiness probe uses tcpSocket on port 9200, so the socket might be open even if the cluster hasn't formed a quorum. Let me check the actual cluster health through the Elasticsearch API with credentials to see what's really happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2625,"cache_read_input_tokens":60375,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2625},"output_tokens":33,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0c965969-72b1-42a7-a03e-f366caf2b51f","uuid":"e2e5d1c8-627a-4996-a7ca-42ef7774a886","request_id":"req_011CcMWKDy2W957DyxQZ9Lff"}
